ooks.google.com/books?id=KcfhAQAAQBAJ|year=2008|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781317968993}}\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|editor-last=Griffin|editor-first=Roger|editorlink=Roger Griffin|title=Fascism, Totalitarianism and Political Religion|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uWfaAAAAQBAJ|year=2005|publisher=Routledge}}\n* {{Cite journal|ref=harv|last=Griffin|first=Roger|authorlink=Roger Griffin|title=The 'Holy Storm': 'Clerical fascism' through the Lens of Modernism|journal=Totalitarian Movements and Political Religions|volume=8|issue=2|year=2007|pages=213\u2013227|doi=10.1080/14690760701321130}}\n* [[Mark Juergensmeyer]]. ''The New Cold War?: Religious Nationalism Confronts the Secular State''. (Berkeley: University of California Press, 1993). ({{ISBN|0-520-08651-1}})\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|last=Kertzer|first=David I.|authorlink=David Kertzer|title=The Pope and Mussolini: The Secret History of Pius XI and the Rise of Fascism in Europe|year=2014|publisher=Oxford University Press|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Xc3QAgAAQBAJ|isbn=9780198716167}}\n* [[Walter Laqueur|Laqueur, Walter]]. 1966. ''Fascism: Past, Present, Future,'' New York: Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1997. {{ISBN|0-19-511793-X}}\n* Nicholas M. Nagy&ndash;Talavera, ''The Green Shirts and the Others: A History of Fascism in Hungary and Romania'' (Ia\u015fi and Oxford: The Center for Romanian Studies, 2001). {{ISBN|973-9432-11-5}}\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|editor-last1=Nelis|editor-first1=Jan|editor-last2=Morelli|editor-first2=Anne|editor-last3=Praet|editor-first3=Danny|title=Catholicism and Fascism in Europe 1918-1945|year=2015|publisher=Georg Olms|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z41wCQAAQBAJ|isbn=9783487421278}}\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|last=Novak|first=Viktor|authorlink=Viktor Novak|title=Magnum Crimen: Half a Century of Clericalism in Croatia|volume=1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=b1jyvQAACAAJ|year=2011|location=Jagodina|publisher=Gambit|isbn=9788676240494}}\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|last=Novak|first=Viktor|authorlink=Viktor Novak|title=Magnum Crimen: Half a Century of Clericalism in Croatia|volume=2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vF9GMwEACAAJ|year=2011|location=Jagodina|publisher=Gambit|isbn=9788676240494}}\n* {{Cite book|last=O'Reilly|first=Charles T.|title=Forgotten Battles: Italy's War of Liberation, 1943-1945|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2LBvZPXmmqoC&pg=PA218|year=2001|publisher=Lexington Books|isbn=978-0-7391-0195-7}}\n* [[Walid Phares]], ''Lebanese Christian Nationalism: The Rise and Fall of an Ethnic Resistance'' (Boulder, Colo.: L. Rienner, 1995). {{ISBN|1-55587-535-1}}\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|last=Phayer|first=Michael|authorlink=Michael Phayer|title=The Catholic Church and the Holocaust, 1930\u20131965|year=2000|location=Bloomington and Indianapolis|publisher=Indiana University Press|url=https://archive.org/details/catholicchurchho00phay|url-access=registration}}\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|last=Phayer|first=Michael|authorlink=Michael Phayer|title=Pius XII, the Holocaust, and the Cold War|year=2008|location=Bloomington and Indianapolis|publisher=Indiana University Press|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CgTZAAAAMAAJ}}\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|last=Pollard|first=John F.|authorlink=John F. Pollard|chapter=Clerical Fascism: Context, Overview and Conclusion|title=Clerical Fascism in Interwar Europe|year=2008|location=London-New York|publisher=Routledge|pages=221-234|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KcfhAQAAQBAJ}}\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|last=Rhodes|first=Anthony|authorlink=Anthony Rhodes|title=The Vatican in the Age of the Dictators 1922-1945|year=1973|location=New York|publisher=Holt, Rinehart and Winston|url=https://archive.org/details/vaticaninageof00rhod|url-access=registration|isbn=9780030077364}}\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|last=Rivelli|first=Marco Aurelio|authorlink=Marco Aurelio Rivelli|year=1998|title=Le g\u00e9nocide occult\u00e9: \u00c9tat Ind\u00e9pendant de Croatie 1941\u20131945|language=French|trans-title=Hidden Genocide: The Independent State of Croatia 1941\u20131945|location=Lausanne|publisher=L'age d'Homme|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QwBnceJfwgUC|isbn=9782825111529}}\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|last=Rivelli|first=Marco Aurelio|authorlink=Marco Aurelio Rivelli|title=L'arcivescovo del genocidio: Monsignor Stepinac, il Vaticano e la dittatura ustascia in Croazia, 1941-1945|language=Italian|trans-title=The Archbishop of Genocide: Monsignor Stepinac, the Vatican and the Usta\u0161e dictatorship in Croatia, 1941-1945|location=Milano|publisher=Kaos|year=1999|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NQtnAAAAMAAJ|isbn=9788879530798}}\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|last=Rivelli|first=Marco Aurelio|authorlink=Marco Aurelio Rivelli|title=\"Dio \u00e8 con noi!\": La Chiesa di Pio XII complice del nazifascismo|language=Italian|trans-title=\"God is with us!\": The Church of Pius XII accomplice to Nazi Fascism|location=Milano|publisher=Kaos|year=2002|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pwPZAAAAMAAJ|isbn=9788879531047}}\n* Livia Rothkirchen, \"Vatican Policy and the \u2018Jewish Problem\u2019 in Independent Slovakia (1939-1945)\" in Michael R. Marrus (ed.),''The Nazi Holocaust'' 3, (Wesport: Meckler, 1989), pp.&nbsp;1306\u20131332. {{ISBN|0-88736-255-9}} or {{ISBN|0-88736-256-7}}\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|last=Rychlak|first=Ronald J.|authorlink=Ronald J. Rychlak|title=Hitler, the War, and the Pope|edition=Revised and expanded|year=2010|location=South Bend|publisher=Our Sunday Visitor|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XmD8CwAAQBAJ|isbn=9781612781969}}\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|editor-last1=Schindley|editor-first1=Wanda|editor-last2=Makara|editor-first2=Petar|title=Jasenovac: Proceedings of the First International Conference and Exhibit on the Jasenovac Concentration Camps|year=2005|publisher=Dallas Publishing|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pAJnAAAAMAAJ}}\n* Leon Volovici, ''Nationalist Ideology and Antisemitism: The Case of Romanian Intellectuals in the 1930s'' (Oxford: Pergamon Press, 1991). {{ISBN|0-08-041024-3}}\n* {{Cite book |last1=Ward |first1=James Mace |title=Priest, Politician, Collaborator: Jozef Tiso and the Making of Fascist Slovakia |date=2013 |publisher=Cornell University Press |location=Ithaka |isbn=978-0-8014-6812-4 |language=en |ref=harv}}\n* Various authors, ''\u2018Clerical Fascism\u2019 in Interwar Europe'', special issue of ''Totalitarian Movements and Political Religions'', Volume 8, Issue 2, 2007.\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Relpolnav}}\n{{Christianity and politics}}\n{{Use British English Oxford spelling|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Clerical Fascism}}\n[[Category:Christian fascists| ]]\n[[Category:Fascism]]\n[[Category:Political ideologies]]\n[[Category:Religion and politics]]\n", "text_old": "{{Fascism sidebar}}\n'''Clerical fascism''' (also '''clero-fascism''' or '''clerico-fascism''') is an ideology that combines the political and economic doctrines of [[fascism]] with [[clericalism]]. The term has been used to describe organizations and movements that combine religious elements with fascism, support by religious organizations for fascism, or fascist regimes in which clergy play a leading role.\n\n== History ==\nThe term ''clerical fascism'' (clero-fascism or clerico-fascism) emerged in the early 1920s in the [[Kingdom of Italy]], referring to the faction of the Roman Catholic [[Italian People's Party (1919\u20131926)|Partito Popolare Italiano]] which supported [[Benito Mussolini]] and his r\u00e9gime; it was supposedly coined by [[Luigi Sturzo|Don Luigi Sturzo]], a priest and [[Christian democracy|Christian democrat]] leader who opposed Mussolini and went into exile in 1924,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://staff.bath.ac.uk/mlsre/ReflectionsonFascismandReligion.htm|title=Reflections on Fascism and Religion |accessdate=2007-02-14 |last=Eatwell |first=Roger |authorlink= |year=2003 |month= |website= |publisher= |pages= |language= |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070501024852/http://staff.bath.ac.uk/mlsre/ReflectionsonFascismandReligion.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-05-01 |quote=}}</ref> although the term had also been used before Mussolini's [[March on Rome]] in 1922 to refer to Catholics in Northern Italy who advocated a synthesis of Roman Catholicism and fascism.<ref>Walter Laqueur, [http://www.laqueur.net/index2.php?r=2&rr=4&id=49 \"The Origins of Fascism: Islamic Fascism, Islamophobia, Antisemitism\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080114011314/http://www.laqueur.net/index2.php?r=2&rr=4&id=49|date=2008-01-14}}, [[Oxford University Press]], 25.10.2006</ref>\n\nSturzo made a distinction between the \"filofascists\", who left the Catholic PPI in 1921 and 1922, and the \"clerical fascists\" who stayed in the party after the [[March on Rome]], advocating collaboration with the fascist government.<ref>Carlo Santulli, ''Filofascisti e Partito Popolare (1923-1926)'' (dissertation), Universit\u00e0 di Roma - La Sapienza, 2001, p. 5.</ref> Eventually, the latter group converged with Mussolini, abandoning the PPI in 1923 and creating the Centro Nazionale Italiano. The PPI was disbanded by the fascist r\u00e9gime in 1926.<ref>Carlo Santulli, Id.</ref>\n\nThe term has since been used by scholars seeking to contrast authoritarian-[[conservatism|conservative]] clerical fascism with more radical variants.<ref>H.R. Trevor-Roper, \"The Phenomenon of Fascism\", in S. Woolf (ed.), ''Fascism in Europe'' (London: Methuen, 1981), especially p. 26. Cited in Roger Eatwell, [http://staff.bath.ac.uk/mlsre/ReflectionsonFascismandReligion.htm \"Reflections on Fascism and Religion\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070501024852/http://staff.bath.ac.uk/mlsre/ReflectionsonFascismandReligion.htm |date=2007-05-01}}</ref> Christian fascists focus on internal religious politics, such as passing laws and regulations that reflect their view of [[Christianity]]. Radicalized forms of Christian fascism or ''clerical fascism'' (clero-fascism or clerico-fascism) were emerging on the far-right of the political spectrum in some European countries during the [[interwar period]] in the first half of the 20th century.{{sfn|Feldman|Turda|Georgescu|2008}}\n\n=== Fascist Italy ===\n{{See also|Kingdom of Italy under Fascism (1922\u20131943)|Roman Question|Freedom of religion in Italy#History}}\n[[File:Firma dei Patti Lateranensi.jpg|thumb|250px|right|[[Mussolini]] (far right) signing the [[Lateran Treaty]] ([[Vatican City]], 11 February 1929)]]\nIn 1870 the newly formed [[Kingdom of Italy]] annexed the remaining [[Papal States]], depriving the Pope of his [[Temporal power (papal)|temporal power]]. However, papal rule in Italy was later [[Lateran Treaty|restored]] by the [[Fascist Italy (1922\u20131943)#Roman Catholic Church|Fascist regime]]<ref name=\"Feinstein\">{{quote|In the period following the signing of the 1929 Lateran Pact, which declared Catholicism as Italy's state religion in the context of a comprehensive regulation of Vatican and Italian government relations, Catholic cultural support for Mussolini is consolidated.|author=Wiley Feinstein|source=''The Civilization of the Holocaust in Italy: Poets, Artists, Saints, Anti-semites'' (2003), p. 19, [[London]]: [[Fairleigh Dickinson University Press]], {{ISBN|0-8386-3988-7}}}}</ref> (albeit on a greatly diminished scale) in 1929 as head of the [[Vatican City]] state;<ref name=\"Feinstein\"/> under [[Mussolini]]'s [[dictatorship]], Roman Catholicism became the [[state religion]] of Fascist Italy.<ref name=\"Feinstein\"/><ref name=\"Kertzer\">{{cite book |last=Kertzer |first=David I. |date=2014 |title=The Pope and Mussolini: The Secret History of Pius XI and the Rise of Fascism in Europe |location=[[New York City|New York]] |publisher=[[Random House]] |pp=196\u2013198 |isbn=978-0-8129-9346-2 |author-link=David I. Kertzer|title-link=The Pope and Mussolini: The Secret History of Pius XI and the Rise of Fascism in Europe}}</ref>\n\nIn March 1929, a nationwide plebiscite was held to publicly endorse the [[Lateran Treaty]]. Opponents were intimidated by the fascist regime: the [[Azione Cattolica|Catholic Action]] organisation (''Azione Cattolica'') and Mussolini claimed that \"no\" votes were of those \"few ill-advised [[Anti-clericalism|anti-clericals]] who refuse to accept the Lateran Pacts\".<ref>Pollard 2014, ''The Vatican and Italian Fascism, 1929-32: A Study in Conflict'', p. 49.</ref> Nearly nine million Italians voted, or 90 per cent of the registered electorate, and only 136,000 voted \"no\".<ref>Pollard 2014, ''The Vatican and Italian Fascism, 1929-32: A Study in Conflict'', p. 61.</ref>\n\nAlmost immediately after the signing of the Treaty, relations between Mussolini and the Church soured again. Mussolini \"referred to Catholicism as, in origin, a minor sect that had spread beyond Palestine only because grafted onto the organization of the Roman empire.\"<ref name=\"dmsmith_162-163\">D.M. Smith 1982, p.&nbsp;162\u2013163</ref> After the concordat, \"he confiscated more issues of Catholic newspapers in the next three months than in the previous seven years.\"<ref name=\"dmsmith_162-163\"/> Mussolini reportedly came close to being [[Excommunication (Catholic Church)|excommunicated]] from the Catholic Church around this time.<ref name=\"dmsmith_162-163\"/>\n\nIn 1938, the [[Italian Racial Laws]] and ''[[Manifesto of Race]]'' were promulgated by the fascist regime, enforced to both [[The Holocaust in Italy|outlaw and persecute Italian Jews]]<ref name=\"Memorial Museum\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ushmm.org/learn/mapping-initiatives/geographies-of-the-holocaust/the-holocaust-in-italy |title=The Holocaust in Italy |last1=Giordano |first1=Alberto |last2=Holian |first2=Anna |date=2018 |website=[[United States Holocaust Memorial Museum]] |access-date=15 August 2018 |quote=In 1938, the Italian Fascist regime under Benito Mussolini enacted a series of racial laws that placed multiple restrictions on the country\u2019s Jewish population. At the time the laws were enacted, it is estimated that about 46,000 Jews lived in Italy, of whom about 9,000 were foreign born and thus subject to further restrictions such as residence requirements. [...] Estimates suggest that between September 1943 and March 1945, about 10,000 Jews were deported. The vast majority perished, principally at [[Auschwitz]].}}</ref> and [[Protestantism in Italy|Protestant Christians]],<ref name=\"Kertzer\"/><ref name=\"Pollard\">{{cite book |last=Pollard |first=John F. |date=2014 |title=The Vatican and Italian Fascism, 1929-32: A Study in Conflict |location=[[Cambridge]] |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |pp=109\u2013111 |isbn=978-0-521-26870-7 |author-link=John F. Pollard}}</ref><ref name=\"Zanini\">{{cite journal |last1=Zanini |first1=Paolo |date=2015 |title=Twenty years of persecution of Pentecostalism in Italy: 1935-1955 |journal=[[Journal of Modern Italian Studies]] |publisher=[[Taylor & Francis]] |volume=20 |issue=5 |pages=686\u2013707 |doi=10.1080/1354571X.2015.1096522}}; {{cite journal |last1=Zanini |first1=Paolo |date=2017 |title=Il culmine della collaborazione antiprotestante tra Stato fascista e Chiesa cattolica: genesi e applicazione della circolare Buffarini Guidi |journal=Societ\u00e0 e Storia |publisher=[[FrancoAngeli]] |volume=155 |pages=139\u2013165 |language=it |doi=10.3280/SS2017-155006}}</ref><ref name=\"AssembliesofGod\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.assembleedidio.org/RP-Speciale/ |title=Risveglio Pentecostale |publisher=[[Assemblies of God in Italy]] |access-date=15 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170501084721/http://www.assembleedidio.org/RP-Speciale/ |archive-date=1 May 2017 |language=It |url-status=dead}}</ref> especially [[Evangelicals]] and [[Pentecostals]].<ref name=\"Pollard\"/><ref name=\"Zanini\"/><ref name=\"AssembliesofGod\"/> Thousands of Italian Jews and a small number of Protestants died in the [[Nazi concentration camps]].<ref name=\"Memorial Museum\"/><ref name=\"AssembliesofGod\"/>\n\nDespite Mussolini's close alliance with Hitler's Germany, Italy did not fully adopt Nazism's genocidal ideology towards the Jews. The Nazis were frustrated by the Italian authorities' refusal to co-operate in the round-ups of Jews, and no Jews were deported prior to the formation of the [[Italian Social Republic]] following the [[Armistice of Cassibile]].{{sfnp|Gilbert|2004|pp=307-308}} In the Italian-occupied [[Independent State of Croatia]], German envoy [[Siegfried Kasche]] advised Berlin that Italian forces had \"apparently been influenced\" by Vatican opposition to German anti-Semitism.{{sfnp|Gilbert|1986|p=466}} As anti-Axis feeling grew in Italy, the use of [[Vatican Radio]] to broadcast papal disapproval of race murder and anti-Semitism angered the Nazis.{{sfnp|Gilbert|2004|pp=308, 311}} Mussolini was overthrown in July 1943, the Germans moved to occupy Italy, and commenced a round-up of Jews.\n\nAround 4% of [[Italian resistance movement|Resistance]] forces were formally Catholic organisations, but Catholics dominated other \"independent groups\" such as the ''[[Fiamme Verdi]]'' and ''Osoppo'' partisans, and there were also Catholic militants in the [[Garibaldi Brigades]], such as [[Benigno Zaccagnini]], who later served as a prominent [[Christian Democracy (Italy)|Christian Democrat]] politician.{{sfnp|O'Reilly|2001|p=178}} In Northern Italy, tensions between Catholics and [[Communist Party of Italy|communists]] in the movement led Catholics to form the ''Fiamme Verdi'' as a separate brigade of Christian Democrats.{{sfnp|O'Reilly|2001|p=218}} After the war, the ideological divisions between the partisans re-emerged, becoming a hallmark of [[Politics of Italy#History of the post-war political landscape|post-war Italian politics]].<ref>{{cite journal |first=John |last=Foot |title=The Legacy of the Italian Resistance |journal=[[History Today]] |date=March 2012 |volume=62 |issue= 3 |url=http://www.historytoday.com/blog/2012/03/legacy-italian-resistance}}</ref>\n\n== Examples of clerical fascism ==\nExamples of political movements involving certain elements of clerical fascism include:\n\n* the [[FET y de las JONS]] of [[Francoist Spain|Spain]] led by [[Catholicism in Spain|Spanish Catholic]] [[Francisco Franco]]\n* the [[National Union (Portugal)|National Union]] in [[Estado Novo (Portugal)|Portugal]] led by Prime Ministers [[Ant\u00f3nio de Oliveira Salazar]] and [[Marcelo Caetano]]\n* the [[National-Christian Defense League]]/[[Iron Guard]] of [[Kingdom of Romania|Romania]] and [[National Legionary State|National Legionary State of Romania]], which was led by the devoutly [[Romanian Orthodox Church|Romanian Orthodox]] [[Corneliu Zelea Codreanu]]\n* the [[Slovak People's Party|Slovak People's Party (\u013dudaks)]] in [[Slovak Republic (1939\u20131945)|Slovakia]] led by President [[Jozef Tiso]], a Catholic priest\n* the [[Ustashe|Usta\u0161e]] movement led by [[Poglavnik]] and [[Prime Minister of Croatia|Prime Minister]] [[Ante Paveli\u0107]] in the [[Independent State of Croatia]]{{sfn|Biondich|2007|p=383-399}} and its [[Catholic clergy involvement with the Usta\u0161e|support from the Croatian Catholic Church]]\n* the [[Serbian Action]], an ultranationalist and clerical fascist<ref name=\"Google books\">Dijana Jela\u010da, Ma\u0161a Kolanovi\u0107, Danijela Lugari\u0107 : [https://books.google.fr/books?id=DE4sDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA327&lpg=PA327&dq=%22serbian+action%22+clero-fascist&source=bl&ots=nGynSEyOc4&sig=ACfU3U3vBccPhEDkc5arYWDpbSxjUtYC-A&hl=fr&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjFzvqFiIzhAhVEzIUKHQXOCEUQ6AEwBnoECAQQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22serbian%20action%22%20clero-fascist&f=false ''The Cultural Life of Capitalism in Yugoslavia: (Post)Socialism and Its Other'']</ref> movement, active in Serbia since 2010.<ref name=\"british council\">{{cite web|author1=Predrag Petrovi\u0107|author2=Isidora Staki\u0107|publisher=[[British Council]]|title=Western Balkans: extremism research forum|date=29 May 2018|url=https://www.britishcouncil.rs/sites/default/files/erf_report_serbia_2018.pdf|website=www.britishcouncil.rs|pages=9\u201310|accessdate=24 October 2018}}</ref>\n* the [[Rexist Party]] in [[German occupation of Belgium during World War II|Belgium]] led by [[L\u00e9on Degrelle]] who was a [[Catholicism in Belgium|Belgian Catholic]].\n* the [[Arrow Cross Party]] of Hungary, whose short-lived Nazi-puppet regime was extremist and fanatic in hating anyone not deemed a true Catholic, and held masses and rituals in churches, etc. \n* the [[Fatherland Front (Austria)|Fatherland Front]] in [[Federal State of Austria|Austria]] led by [[Catholicism in Austria|Austrian Catholic]] Chancellors [[Engelbert Dollfuss]] and [[Kurt Schuschnigg]].\n* the [[Leon Rupnik]] regime in [[Province of Ljubljana|Slovenia]] which was [[Religion in Slovenia|predominantly Roman Catholic]].\n* the [[Brazilian Integralist Action]] in [[Vargas Era|Brazil]] led by [[Christianity in Brazil|Brazilian Catholic]] [[Pl\u00ednio Salgado]].\n* the [[Lapua Movement]] and the [[Patriotic People's Movement (Finland)|Patriotic People's Movement]] (IKL) in [[Finland]] led by the [[Protestantism in Finland|Lutherans]] ([[Her\u00e4nn\u00e4isyys|k\u00f6rtti]]) [[Vihtori Kosola]] and [[Vilho Annala]] respectively. Pastor [[Elias Simojoki]] led the IKL\u2019s youth organization Sinimustat.\n* the [[British Union of Fascists]] in the [[United Kingdom]] led by [[Oswald Mosley]] which preached religious tolerance between [[Protestantism in the United Kingdom|British Protestants]] and [[Catholicism in the United Kingdom|British Catholics]] and espoused the former as its official faith.\n* the [[Silver Legion of America]] in the [[United States]] led by [[William Dudley Pelley]] which combined [[Christianity in the United States|American Christianity]] (specifically [[Protestantism in the United States|Protestantism]]) with [[White nationalism#United States|American white nationalism]].\n* the [[National Radical Camp]] in [[Second Polish Republic|Poland]] led by [[Boleslaw Piasecki]], [[Henryk Rossman]], Tadeusz Gluzinski and [[Jan Mosdorf]] which heavily incorporated [[Catholicism in Poland|Polish Catholicism]] into its ideology especially the Falangist faction.\n* [[German Christians]] of the [[Nazi Party]] in [[Nazi Germany]] led by [[Ludwig Muller]] which attempted to unify [[Protestantism in Germany|German Protestants]] during the ''[[Kirchenkampf]]'' but failed.\n* [[Metaxism]] and the [[4th of August Regime]] in [[Kingdom of Greece|Greece]] which was led by [[Ioannis Metaxas]] and heavily supported the [[Greek Orthodox Church]].\n\nScholars who accept the term ''clerical fascism'' nonetheless debate which of the listed examples should be dubbed \"clerical fascist\", with the Usta\u0161e being the most widely included. In the above cited examples, the degree of official Catholic support and clerical influence over lawmaking and government varies. Moreover, several authors reject the concept of a ''clerical fascist r\u00e9gime'', arguing that an entire fascist r\u00e9gime does not become \"clerical\" if elements of the clergy support it, while others are not prepared to use the term \"clerical fascism\" outside the context of what they call the ''fascist epoch'', between the ends of the two [[world wars]] (1918\u20131945).{{sfn|Griffin|2007|p=213-227}}\n\nSome scholars regard certain contemporary movements as forms of clerical fascism, including [[Christian Identity]] and [[Christian Reconstructionism]] in the [[United States]];<ref name = \"berlet1\">{{cite book|authorlink1=Chip Berlet|last1=Berlet|first1=Chip|editor1-last=Griffin|editor1-first=Roger|title=Fascism as a Totalitarian Movement|date=2005|publisher=Routledge|location=New York|isbn=978-0-415-34793-8|page=196|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uWfaAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA196&lpg=PA196&dq=%22christian+reconstructionism%22+%22clerical+fascism%22&source=bl&ots=ftyO7Ek_ON&sig=M8Ip-zxpyALffmp-5OmLJ35jgfk&hl=en&sa=X&ei=PlVxVMOnNPGHsQTuyoHoBA&ved=0CCgQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=%22christian%20reconstructionism%22%20%22clerical%20fascism%22&f=false|accessdate=23 November 2014|chapter=Christian Identity: The Apocalyptic Style, Political Religion, Palingenesis, and Neo-Fascism|quote=\"Lyons and I put Christian Identity into the category of clerical fascism, and we also included the militant theocratic Protestant movement called Christian Reconstructionism... a case can be made for... the Hindu nationalist (Hinduvata) Bharatiya Janata Party in India (which grew out of the Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh Hindu religious movement).\"|ref=berlet1}}</ref> \"the most virulent form\" of [[Islamic fundamentalism]],<ref name=berlet2>{{cite book|authorlink1=Chip Berlet|last1=Berlet|first1=Chip|editor1-last=Langman|editor1-first=Lauren|editor2-last=Kalekin-Fishman|editor2-first=Devorah|title=The Evolution of Alienation: Trauma, Promise, and the Millennium|page=130|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nIZctokjRlQC&pg=PA130&lpg=PA130&dq=%22islamic+fundamentalism%22+%22clerical+fascism%22&source=bl&ots=xH9OU1WWJk&sig=R6YMI2lpBWkT2GAkbZEUK2KqWCU&hl=en&sa=X&ei=XlVxVMvaNaaMsQTlkoD4Dw&ved=0CCsQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=%22islamic%20fundamentalism%22%20%22clerical%20fascism%22&f=false|chapter=When Alienation Turns Right: Populist Conspiracism, the Apocalyptic Style, and Neofascist Movements|quote=\"In the most virulent form, theocratic Islamic fundamentalism could be a form of clerical fascism (theocratic fascism built around existing institutionalized clerics). This is a disputed view...\"}}</ref> [[Islamism]];<ref name = \"mozaffari1\">{{cite journal|title=What is Islamism? History and Definition of a Concept|last1=Mozaffari|first1=Mehdi|journal=Totalitarian Movements and Political Religions|date=March 2007|volume=8|issue=1|pages=17\u201333|quote=\"\u2018Clerical fascism\u2019 is perhaps the nearest concept which comes closest to Islamism.\"\n|url=http://pure.au.dk/portal/files/22326292/What_is_Islamism_Totalitarian_Movements_article.pdf|accessdate=23 November 2014|doi=10.1080/14690760601121622}}</ref> and militant [[Hindu nationalism]] in [[India]].<ref name=\"berlet1\" />\n\nThe political theorist [[Roger Griffin]] warns against the \"hyperinflation of clerical fascism\".{{sfn|Griffin|2007|p=215}} According to Griffin, the use of the term \"clerical fascism\" should be limited to \"the peculiar forms of politics that arise when religious clerics and professional theologians are drawn either into collusion with the ''secular'' ideology of fascism (an occurrence particularly common in [[interwar period|interwar]] [[Europe]]); or, more rarely, manage to mix a theologically illicit cocktail of deeply held religious beliefs with a fascist commitment to saving the nation or race from decadence or collapse\".{{sfn|Griffin|2007|p=213}} Griffin adds that \"clerical fascism\" \"should never be used to characterize a political movement or a regime in its entirety, since it can at most be a faction within fascism\", while he defines fascism as \"a revolutionary, secular variant of ultranationalism bent on the total rebirth of society through human agency\".{{sfn|Griffin|2007|p=224}}\n\nIn the case of the [[Slovak State]], some scholars have rejected the use of clerical fascism as a label for the regime and for Jozef Tiso in particular. Slovak historian [[\u013dubom\u00edr Lipt\u00e1k]] has argued that \"clerofascism\" is similar to [[Judeo-Bolshevism]] in that both labels\nsought \"to compromise one [component] with the other and both mutually\".{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=267}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Alois Hudal]]\n* [[Catholic Church and Nazi Germany]]\n* [[Christofascism]]\n* [[Islamofascism]]\n* [[National Union (Italy, 1923)]]\n* [[Neo-v\u00f6lkisch movements]]\n* [[Positive Christianity]]\n* [[Religious nationalism]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* [[Walter K. Andersen]]. \"Bharatiya Janata Party: Searching for 